00:11:12,660 --> 00:11:15,050
字幕
So what I got from Bruce as a performer is...

173
00:11:15,400 --> 00:11:20,200
字幕
You know, most performers perform like this, right? Straight up.

174
00:11:20,300 --> 00:11:23,630
字幕
Me, perform from the side,

175
00:11:24,110 --> 00:11:27,310
字幕
sort of like how Bruce used to always, you know,

176
00:11:27,310 --> 00:11:28,920
字幕
be ready for combat like this.

177
00:11:28,920 --> 00:11:32,050
字幕
Honestly expressing yourself, like me being a dancer,

178
00:11:32,050 --> 00:11:34,100
字幕
that's what it's all about.

179
00:11:34,680 --> 00:11:39,010
字幕
That's another big, big philosophy from him that I take with me to this day.

180
00:11:39,010 --> 00:11:42,510
字幕
So I'll be performing like, "Bah, bah! Bah, bah, bah, bah!"

181
00:11:43,580 --> 00:11:46,260
字幕
I keep trying to dig deeper and deeper within myself

182
00:11:46,260 --> 00:11:50,270
字幕
and find that fluidity that no one can replicate.

183
00:11:55,420 --> 00:11:58,240
字幕
That's the vibe that Bruce Lee taught me.

184
00:11:58,320 --> 00:11:59,500
字幕
It's to always bring it.

185
00:11:59,500 --> 00:12:01,280
字幕
That's what I get from Bruce.

186
00:12:02,840 --> 00:12:07,540
字幕
- And when did you leave Hong Kong? - 1959, when I was 18.

187
00:12:07,620 --> 00:12:11,150
字幕
It had gotten a little difficult with the police on one side

188
00:12:11,150 --> 00:12:13,420
字幕
and with gangs on the other side.

189
00:12:13,420 --> 00:12:15,810
字幕
He beat this kid up, but he didn't know that the kid

190
00:12:15,810 --> 00:12:19,230
字幕
was the son of a high-ranking police officer in Hong Kong.

191
00:12:19,230 --> 00:12:22,390
字幕
He got into so many street fights that by 18, his father gave him $100

192
00:12:22,390 --> 00:12:23,740
字幕
and sent him off to America.

193
00:12:24,680 --> 00:12:28,650
字幕
If he wanted his immigration status to be US citizen,

194
00:12:28,650 --> 00:12:31,300
字幕
then he had to return by the time he was 18.

195
00:12:31,300 --> 00:12:33,620
字幕
To go when you're still a star is very strange,

196
00:12:33,620 --> 00:12:37,970
字幕
because he could have kept doing films, but they wanted him to go,

197
00:12:38,660 --> 00:12:41,990
字幕
to make the right decision of where he's going next.

198
00:12:58,090 --> 00:13:01,240
字幕
In Seattle, my father started teaching martial arts.

199
00:13:01,240 --> 00:13:06,220
字幕
He didn't ever look at people because of their race or their stature in life.

200
00:13:06,220 --> 00:13:09,810
字幕
If you had a sincere interest in martial arts, he would teach you.

201
00:13:09,810 --> 00:13:12,110
字幕
Taky Kimura was really his best friend.

202
00:13:12,110 --> 00:13:16,080
字幕
Taky became his first assistant instructor in his first school,

203
00:13:16,080 --> 00:13:18,830
字幕
the Jun Fan Gung Fu Institute, in Seattle, Washington.

204
00:13:19,490 --> 00:13:21,740
字幕
Bruce used to come to my high school

205
00:13:21,740 --> 00:13:25,100
字幕
and he used to teach in the Chinese philosophy class.

206
00:13:25,100 --> 00:13:29,300
字幕
He was five years older than we were and I do remember my heart going,

207
00:13:29,300 --> 00:13:32,060
字幕
"Pah, pah, pah", you know, "He is sure cute."

208
00:13:32,460 --> 00:13:36,430
字幕
It wasn't long after that that I started taking gung fu lessons from him,

209
00:13:36,430 --> 00:13:41,130
字幕
and my relationship with him changed more from just a student

210
00:13:41,130 --> 00:13:46,040
字幕
to actually feeling that maybe, maybe there could be a connection between us.

211
00:13:46,040 --> 00:13:48,430
字幕
We both attended the University of Washington.

212
00:13:48,430 --> 00:13:51,160
字幕
We would get together on campus

213
00:13:51,160 --> 00:13:53,150
字幕
and attend our classes,

214
00:13:53,150 --> 00:13:56,540
字幕
occasionally, when we weren't doing gung fu or something else.

215
00:13:56,540 --> 00:13:59,120
字幕
And then when we were both done with our classes,

216
00:13:59,120 --> 00:14:00,800
字幕
we would rush back to his studio,

217
00:14:00,800 --> 00:14:03,610
字幕
which was just right there in the university district,

218
00:14:03,610 --> 00:14:07,150
字幕
and we'd turn on the TV and watch General Hospital every day.

219
00:14:07,150 --> 00:14:10,720
字幕
And it was like, "We have to get there. It's almost three o'clock!"

220
00:14:13,160 --> 00:14:15,800
字幕
In the '60s, marriages were happening in California.

221
00:14:15,800 --> 00:14:19,930
字幕
In the rest of the country there were no interracial marriages. It was difficult.

222
00:14:19,930 --> 00:14:23,520
字幕
My mother was not thrilled when we decided to get married

223
00:14:23,520 --> 00:14:28,550
字幕
and didn't want her daughter to have to suffer any negativity from others.

224
00:14:28,550 --> 00:14:31,330
字幕
The ban on interracial marriage was lifted in 1968.

225
00:14:31,330 --> 00:14:34,090
字幕
That didn't mean the ban lifted in people's hearts.

226
00:14:34,090 --> 00:14:37,060
字幕
Bruce was very strong in saying,

227
00:14:37,060 --> 00:14:41,540
字幕
"I want to marry Linda. I know that we are a good match."

228
00:14:41,770 --> 00:14:45,850
字幕
And so we did get married. It was really hard on my mother.

229
00:14:45,850 --> 00:14:48,840
字幕
But it wasn't long before she came to love Bruce very much.

230
00:14:48,840 --> 00:14:53,280
字幕
It's so important to know that it was his wife Linda that grounded him.

231
00:14:53,280 --> 00:14:55,130
字幕
She was his rock.

232
00:14:55,130 --> 00:15:00,540
字幕
As a couple, we really did not suffer any prejudice from outsiders,

233
00:15:00,540 --> 00:15:05,450
字幕
and I think this had a great deal to do with Bruce's overwhelming personality.

234
00:15:07,160 --> 00:15:10,960
字幕
I absolutely recognise that my uncle was a gorgeous man.

235
00:15:10,960 --> 00:15:13,990
字幕
He's got swagger. We love his style.

236
00:15:13,990 --> 00:15:17,840
字幕
He had style the way Muhammad Ali had style in the ring.

237
00:15:18,430 --> 00:15:21,900
字幕
He was like the Elvis of martial arts. He looked like a movie star.

238
00:15:21,900 --> 00:15:25,830
字幕
He was always such a snappy dresser and so handsome.

239
00:15:25,830 --> 00:15:28,900
字幕
I've heard the term that he's put balls on Chinese men.

240
00:15:28,900 --> 00:15:35,330
字幕
He's shown that the Chinese man can be, you know, sexy and hot and enticing.

241
00:15:35,330 --> 00:15:38,120
字幕
I'm trying to copy his hair.

242
00:15:38,120 --> 00:15:40,220
字幕
That's why my hair is long.

243
00:15:41,660 --> 00:15:46,890
字幕
After Bruce Lee, my God, Chinese men, they're a force to be reckoned with.

244
00:15:46,890 --> 00:15:49,980
字幕
They're invincible. So that's an amazing transformation.

245
00:15:50,190 --> 00:15:54,770
字幕
He's one of a kind and extremely attractive.

246
00:15:54,770 --> 00:15:59,110
字幕
That would be for both straight women and a lot of gay men that I know too.

247
00:15:59,110 --> 00:16:00,170
字幕
Let's just put it this way.

248
00:16:00,170 --> 00:16:04,630
字幕
I think the one thing that's missing in my life right now is Bruce Lee.

249
00:16:04,630 --> 00:16:06,100
字幕
A man like Bruce Lee.

250
00:16:10,780 --> 00:16:13,600
字幕
The first internationals were in Long Beach.

251
00:16:13,600 --> 00:16:16,740
字幕
I was instructed to take out Bruce Lee. He was the guest.

252
00:16:16,740 --> 00:16:18,860
字幕
So I was sort of like the tour guide for him.

253
00:16:18,860 --> 00:16:22,080
字幕
He demonstrated his art before he even demonstrated

254
00:16:22,080 --> 00:16:23,840
字幕
in front of the black-belt audience.

255
00:16:24,060 --> 00:16:27,610
字幕
In the hotel room he says, "You can use everything, you can side-kick,

256
00:16:27,610 --> 00:16:30,320
字幕
you can round-kick, and I'll just use my jab."

257
00:16:30,870 --> 00:16:34,260
字幕
When he knocked me out, it was more like a hook.

258
00:16:35,470 --> 00:16:39,550
字幕
It sort of came off the side like that. The ease in which he did it,

259
00:16:39,550 --> 00:16:42,190
字幕
and explaining while he was doing it to me,

260
00:16:42,190 --> 00:16:44,070
字幕
that was mind-boggling for me.

261
00:16:44,070 --> 00:16:46,970
字幕
It was like a bad dream, like the dreams where you can't run.

262
00:16:46,970 --> 00:16:51,080
字幕
When Bruce Lee came up and did his performance of his gung fu,

263
00:16:51,080 --> 00:16:53,390
字幕
it was something I had never seen before.

264
00:16:53,390 --> 00:16:56,610
字幕
He said, "The individual is more important in any style or system."

265
00:16:56,610 --> 00:16:59,050
字幕
I said, "I need to train with a man like this."

266
00:16:59,050 --> 00:17:01,360
字幕
He was just so ahead of the times.

267
00:17:01,360 --> 00:17:07,390
字幕
He'd go to Ed Parker's events in Long Beach and they treated him like a god.

268
00:17:07,390 --> 00:17:11,860
字幕
When he did his one-thumb push-ups, you could hear a pin drop.

269
00:17:11,860 --> 00:17:14,570
字幕
He showed his speed, showed his power,

270
00:17:14,570 --> 00:17:16,420
字幕
showed his one-inch punch.

271
00:17:16,970 --> 00:17:19,880
字幕
People say, "Bruce Lee is the fastest person on earth."

272
00:17:19,880 --> 00:17:22,460
字幕
He did these things so realistically

273
00:17:22,460 --> 00:17:26,090
字幕
that people didn't know if it was show business or the real McCoy.

274
00:17:26,090 --> 00:17:29,170
字幕
When Bruce did the demonstration in 1964,

275
00:17:29,170 --> 00:17:33,640
字幕
before he had even come back to Oakland where we lived at the time,

276
00:17:33,640 --> 00:17:37,210
字幕
I had received a phone call from William Dozier's office.

277
00:17:37,210 --> 00:17:41,530
字幕
Jay Sebring, the famous hair stylist, happened to see my father

278
00:17:41,530 --> 00:17:45,460
字幕
at the Long Beach internationals, and he cut the hair of William Dozier.

279
00:17:45,460 --> 00:17:47,790
字幕
He said, "You have to see this guy. He's amazing."

280
00:17:47,790 --> 00:17:50,190
字幕
When Bruce came home, I said to him,

281
00:17:50,190 --> 00:17:52,810
字幕
"You need to call this guy back, William Dozier."

282
00:17:52,810 --> 00:17:56,370
字幕
"He's a producer in Hollywood and he wants to see you."

283
00:17:56,370 --> 00:17:59,000
字幕
That was the first inkling that,

284
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:03,800
字幕
"Wow, I might be able to do something in Hollywood."

285
00:18:04,800 --> 00:18:07,070
字幕
Look directly into the camera.

286
00:18:07,070 --> 00:18:12,020
字幕
Very dapper. He's got the suit and the tie, you know, white shirt.

287
00:18:12,020 --> 00:18:13,770
字幕
He's so elegant.

288
00:18:14,060 --> 00:18:16,530
字幕
But he feels like a coiled cobra.

289
00:18:16,530 --> 00:18:19,150
字幕
- You've just had a baby boy? - Yeah.

290
00:18:19,150 --> 00:18:21,680
字幕
And you've lost a little sleep over it, have you?

291
00:18:21,680 --> 00:18:23,010
字幕
Three nights.

292
00:18:23,150 --> 00:18:26,440
字幕
He was 24, and he went in there, it's almost like,

293
00:18:26,440 --> 00:18:29,430
字幕
"You're lucky that I'm here auditioning for you."

294
00:18:29,430 --> 00:18:32,180
字幕
There is the finger jab There is the punch.

295
00:18:32,180 --> 00:18:35,530
字幕
Just the poise he had said it all.

296
00:18:35,530 --> 00:18:37,160
字幕
There is the back fist and elbow.

297
00:18:37,160 --> 00:18:41,470
字幕
Even in conversation, you could feel his explosive nature.

298
00:18:41,470 --> 00:18:44,570
字幕
Of course, then they use legs, straight to the groin or come up.

299
00:18:44,570 --> 00:18:47,140
字幕
That's a special kind of star power.

300
00:18:47,250 --> 00:18:49,290
字幕
Or, if I can back up a little bit,

301
00:18:49,500 --> 00:18:51,920
字幕
we stop at the... and then come back.

302
00:18:53,230 --> 00:18:54,600
字幕
- Alright. - This kind of works.

303
00:18:54,600 --> 00:18:57,490
字幕
He never had any intention of going into show business.

304
00:18:57,490 --> 00:18:59,570
字幕
His passion was his martial arts,

305
00:18:59,570 --> 00:19:04,130
字幕
so he had a school in Seattle and a second school in Oakland.

306
00:19:04,130 --> 00:19:08,400
字幕
His plan was to open many, many schools all over the county.

307
00:19:08,400 --> 00:19:12,350
字幕
Obviously he started with the classical Chinese arts, which is wing chun.

308
00:19:12,350 --> 00:19:17,180
字幕
And then everyone knows about the fight in 1964 in Oakland.

309
00:19:22,830 --> 00:19:25,580
字幕
There's the famous story about how he was challenged

310
00:19:25,580 --> 00:19:27,740
字幕
by the Chinese community in Oakland,

311
00:19:27,740 --> 00:19:33,210
字幕
and he had to defend the right to teach his art to non-Chinese people.

312
00:19:33,210 --> 00:19:37,230
字幕
You and this entire society are useless in this country. You are archaic.

313
00:19:37,230 --> 00:19:40,370
字幕
And you're a fool to think that you can break away from us

314
00:19:40,370 --> 00:19:41,880
字幕
merely because you choose to.

315
00:19:41,880 --> 00:19:45,300
字幕
To prove Bruce Lee was wrong, he was a fake and a fraud,

316
00:19:45,300 --> 00:19:48,950
字幕
the Chinese traditionalists sent somebody over to fight him.

317
00:19:49,040 --> 00:19:51,890
字幕
The Chinese sent someone to shut down the school.

318
00:19:51,890 --> 00:19:55,150
字幕
Shut down or thrown down, and Bruce chose throw down.

319
00:19:55,150 --> 00:19:57,820
字幕
The fight was to be held at Bruce's school.

320
00:19:57,820 --> 00:20:02,800
字幕
If Bruce lost the fight, he would have to stop teaching non-Chinese people.

321
00:20:02,800 --> 00:20:07,940
字幕
Anything that forces you to review your dogmas,

322
00:20:07,940 --> 00:20:10,190
字幕
most people don't respond too well to it.

323
00:20:10,380 --> 00:20:13,340
字幕
I was there, eight months pregnant with Brandon,

324
00:20:13,340 --> 00:20:16,860
字幕
and these elders arrived from San Francisco,

325
00:20:16,860 --> 00:20:21,470
字幕
led by Wong Jack Man, who was going to be the opponent in this challenge.

326
00:20:21,470 --> 00:20:23,980
字幕
They came and they had this big match.

327
00:20:23,980 --> 00:20:28,160
字幕
I didn't have a shred of a doubt about how this would come out.

328
00:20:28,500 --> 00:20:33,330
字幕
Wong Jack Man started to run around the room trying to get away from Bruce,

329
00:20:33,330 --> 00:20:37,910
字幕
and it took three minutes for Bruce to get him down on the ground

330
00:20:37,910 --> 00:20:39,850
字幕
and say, "Do you give UP?"

331
00:20:41,160 --> 00:20:44,250
字幕
So Wong Jack Man and those people all left.

332
00:20:44,460 --> 00:20:47,640
字幕
And I remember so clearly in my mind's eye

333
00:20:47,640 --> 00:20:52,370
字幕
Bruce sitting on the steps in the back of the studio

334
00:20:52,370 --> 00:20:54,380
字幕
with his head in his hands.

335
00:20:54,380 --> 00:20:56,030
字幕
And she said, "What's the matter?"

336
00:20:56,030 --> 00:20:59,920
字幕
That was the fight that he realised the classical arts were not working for him.

337
00:20:59,920 --> 00:21:02,570
字幕
He should have put that guy down sooner.

338
00:21:02,570 --> 00:21:06,540
字幕
Bruce Lee doesn't beat him fast enough, so he goes off to rethink it all,

339
00:21:06,540 --> 00:21:10,180
字幕
and these tales all had the structure of myth and fantasy.

340
00:21:10,180 --> 00:21:12,040
字幕
Little parables about the master.

341
00:21:12,040 --> 00:21:15,290
字幕
He said, "My training in wing chun, my classical art,

342
00:21:15,290 --> 00:21:18,510
字幕
didn't prepare me for this kind of a battle."

343
00:21:18,510 --> 00:21:22,930
字幕
That was the beginning of the evolution of his own way of martial arts.

344
00:21:25,670 --> 00:21:30,560
字幕
If you read the notes that he left behind, 1965 he starts to write,

345
00:21:30,560 --> 00:21:32,860
字幕
"My style is Western fencing,

346
00:21:32,860 --> 00:21:34,300
字幕
Western boxing and wing chun."

347
00:21:34,300 --> 00:21:37,440
字幕
He said he owe our knowledge to the wing chun,

348
00:21:37,440 --> 00:21:40,000
字幕
but we're gonna go beyond the wing chun.

349
00:21:40,000 --> 00:21:41,170
字幕
Bruce Lee took a lot from boxing.

350
00:21:41,170 --> 00:21:46,440
字幕
He felt boxing was more realistic in that you were trading blows.

351
00:21:46,440 --> 00:21:51,010
字幕
He likes the boxing footwork. It's alive, it's moving and it changes.

352
00:21:51,010 --> 00:21:55,020
字幕
He was totally invested in watching boxing films,

353
00:21:55,020 --> 00:22:00,050
字幕
going way back to Jack Johnson, Gene Tunney, Dempsey.

354
00:22:00,050 --> 00:22:03,060
字幕
What he took from Dempsey was the kinetic chain,

355
00:22:03,060 --> 00:22:05,960
字幕
how to generate power, the importance of a good jab.

356
00:22:05,960 --> 00:22:08,950
字幕
There's a lot about the alignment of the body.

357
00:22:09,200 --> 00:22:11,850
字幕
Bruce had a huge collection of boxing films

358
00:22:11,850 --> 00:22:14,620
字幕
and he thought the world of Muhammad Ali.

359
00:22:14,620 --> 00:22:18,020
字幕
What he would do was very unique. I once came in, lights were all out.

360
00:22:18,130 --> 00:22:22,030
字幕
And he's watching this 8mm film and he's watching it backwards.

361
00:22:22,030 --> 00:22:25,600
字幕
Ali had a left-foot forward stance and Bruce a right foot forward.

362
00:22:25,600 --> 00:22:28,140
字幕
So he would run the films backward in the film editor

363
00:22:28,140 --> 00:22:30,800
字幕
and study them meticulously.

364
00:22:30,800 --> 00:22:33,230
字幕
He would stretch and read

365
00:22:33,730 --> 00:22:37,280
字幕
and review on 8mm film of a boxer at the same time.

366
00:22:37,280 --> 00:22:40,730
字幕
According to John Saxon, his co-star on Enter the Dragon,

367
00:22:40,730 --> 00:22:44,030
字幕
John asked him, "Why do you have all these boxing films on Ali?"

368
00:22:44,030 --> 00:22:47,360
字幕
And Bruce said, "Because one day I'm gonna fight him."

369
00:22:47,950 --> 00:22:51,760
字幕
If I was to fight Bruce Lee, Bruce Lee was so quick, so smooth,

370
00:22:51,760 --> 00:22:55,530
字幕
but the one thing that negates speed on a fighter is pressure,

371
00:22:55,530 --> 00:22:56,960
字幕
and I was a pressure fighter.

372
00:22:57,710 --> 00:23:00,250
字幕
With Bruce Lee, you gotta go inside, smother him

373
00:23:00,250 --> 00:23:03,980
字幕
and outmuscle him. But you can't fight a dude like that outside.

374
00:23:03,980 --> 00:23:07,430
字幕
I see Bruce leading off with some long-ass kicks

375
00:23:07,430 --> 00:23:11,620
字幕
and Boom Boom gets pissed off and tries to give him some body punches.

376
00:23:11,620 --> 00:23:13,770
字幕
And when you get close, then Bruce, I'm sure,

377
00:23:13,770 --> 00:23:16,270
字幕
would be trying to bring knees and high head kicks,

378
00:23:16,270 --> 00:23:19,860
字幕
and I'd throw an upper cut, bring the elbow across.

379
00:23:19,860 --> 00:23:24,740
字幕
And he's gonna be trying to counter me, so I have to bob and weave inside.

380
00:23:24,740 --> 00:23:28,410
字幕
Bruce gets it to the ground and arm-bars him or guillotines him.

381
00:23:29,670 --> 00:23:31,610
字幕
It would have been a good time.

382
00:23:35,100 --> 00:23:37,890
字幕
People are watching this going, "He took more shots than we thought."

383
00:23:37,890 --> 00:23:39,560
字幕
"He absolutely has lost his mind

384
00:23:39,560 --> 00:23:41,520
字幕
thinking he can do that against Bruce Lee."

385
00:23:43,430 --> 00:23:47,120
字幕
Ray was good to the body. Then he'd eventually get that hook on you.

386
00:23:47,120 --> 00:23:50,780
字幕
Bruce wouldn't know how to stop it. Why? Because he never did it.

387
00:23:53,400 --> 00:23:56,930
字幕
People bring up the question: Was Bruce Lee a real fighter?

388
00:24:01,240 --> 00:24:04,990
字幕
Bruce was a brilliant fighter. I saw him beat up a guy on Enter the Dragon.

389
00:24:04,990 --> 00:24:08,340
字幕
It was a gang banger, a tong member, who started giving him a bad time.

390
00:24:08,340 --> 00:24:11,340
字幕
Pound for pound, I think he's probably one of the best fighters.

391
00:24:11,340 --> 00:24:14,460
字幕
He had tons of street fights and with that speed and footwork,

392
00:24:14,460 --> 00:24:16,240
字幕
he'd be a hell of a 135-pounder.

393
00:24:16,240 --> 00:24:18,830
字幕
He was a 130-something-pound lethal weapon.

394
00:24:24,810 --> 00:24:26,900
字幕
He has all the attributes that make a good fighter:

395
00:24:26,900 --> 00:24:31,540
字幕
The agility, the balance, the coordination, the dexterity.

396
00:24:38,150 --> 00:24:41,440
字幕
People say was he the toughest man that ever lived?

397
00:24:41,440 --> 00:24:43,790
字幕
He was 130, 135 pounds.

398
00:24:43,790 --> 00:24:47,780
字幕
You'd grab him and, you know, out the window.

399
00:24:47,780 --> 00:24:49,850
字幕
And that isn't to put him down.

400
00:24:49,850 --> 00:24:52,890
字幕
He was an entertainer, and the best.

401
00:24:52,890 --> 00:24:55,710
字幕
If he wanted to become an MMA fighter today,

402
00:24:55,710 --> 00:24:59,880
字幕
he would easily have been that fighter that everyone fears.

403
00:24:59,880 --> 00:25:02,580
字幕
His technique was beautiful, perfect technique.

404
00:25:02,580 --> 00:25:05,020
字幕
I don't care how good you are, 135lb wrestler,

405
00:25:05,020 --> 00:25:07,860
字幕
you fight Brock Lesnar, you're gonna lose.

406
00:25:07,860 --> 00:25:10,750
字幕
The bigger guy equally trained is always gonna beat the littler guy.

407
00:25:12,080 --> 00:25:14,120
字幕
But the fact is, it wasn't about mass.

408
00:25:14,120 --> 00:25:16,920
字幕
He would just put it down no matter how big you were.

409
00:25:16,920 --> 00:25:20,740
字幕
But, then again, everybody's chin is different, you know?

410
00:25:22,380 --> 00:25:26,440
字幕
Whether Bruce Lee was a great fighter or wasn't a great fighter

411
00:25:26,440 --> 00:25:30,070
字幕
doesn't make any difference to his cultural and historical importance,

412
00:25:30,070 --> 00:25:33,060
字幕
because his films changed the world.

413
00:25:34,900 --> 00:25:39,060
字幕
You got the job on The Green Hornet, where you played Kato, the chauffeur,

414
00:25:39,060 --> 00:25:41,180
字幕
mainly because you're the only Chinese-looking guy

415
00:25:41,180 --> 00:25:44,280
字幕
who could pronounce the name of the leading character, Britt Reid.

416
00:25:44,890 --> 00:25:46,990
字幕
I made that as a joke, of course.

417
00:25:48,620 --> 00:25:50,120
字幕
And it's a heck of a name, man.

418
00:25:50,120 --> 00:25:53,980
字幕
Every time I said it at that time, I was superconscious.

419
00:25:55,040 --> 00:25:56,730
字幕
Mr Reid's residence.

420
00:25:56,730 --> 00:25:59,500
字幕
As a kid, we watched Green Hornet for him.

421
00:26:00,910 --> 00:26:03,560
字幕
We could care less about Green Hornet.

422
00:26:03,560 --> 00:26:06,160
字幕
He had a fly car, I'll give him props for the car,

423
00:26:06,160 --> 00:26:08,490
字幕
but Kato was incredible.

424
00:26:08,490 --> 00:26:11,150
字幕
Everybody in the neighbourhood was fighting to be Bruce Lee,

425
00:26:11,150 --> 00:26:12,210
字幕
not the Green Hornet.

426
00:26:12,210 --> 00:26:15,110
字幕
A lot of stunt guys didn't know how to react.

427
00:26:15,110 --> 00:26:19,190
字幕
You do the old John Wayne, you throw a punch and the guy goes down.

428
00:26:19,190 --> 00:26:22,350
字幕
With him, it's boom, boom, boom, boom, lightning fast.

429
00:26:22,350 --> 00:26:25,320
字幕
There's a shot of Bruce and he's doing a kick,

430
00:26:25,320 --> 00:26:29,480
字幕
and his thigh, his inner thigh, is flat against his chest.

431
00:26:29,480 --> 00:26:32,610
字幕
And we would just look at that kick like, "Are you kidding me?"

432
00:26:32,610 --> 00:26:35,440
字幕
"Look how incredible this guy can kick."

433
00:26:37,840 --> 00:26:42,070
字幕
I think about what my dad said about his first foray into Hollywood.

434
00:26:42,070 --> 00:26:45,340
字幕
There were all these seasoned actors doing their thing,

435
00:26:45,340 --> 00:26:48,040
字幕
and he felt like the only robot in the room.

436
00:26:48,040 --> 00:26:51,450
字幕
That's something I can really relate to in my life, back when I was acting,

437
00:26:51,450 --> 00:26:55,920
字幕
and I was trying so hard to impress the right people.

438
00:26:55,920 --> 00:26:58,550
字幕
When I did The Green Hornet, I was not being myself

439
00:26:58,550 --> 00:27:02,260
字幕
and I'm trying to accumulate external security,

440
00:27:02,260 --> 00:27:03,980
字幕
external technique,

441
00:27:03,980 --> 00:27:07,960
字幕
but never to ask what Bruce Lee would have done.

442
00:27:07,960 --> 00:27:11,470
字幕
The beauty was that he immediately said, "I'm not gonna do that any more."

443
00:27:11,470 --> 00:27:14,340
字幕
Sort of an awakening moment for him.

444
00:27:14,340 --> 00:27:17,440
字幕
By the way, I did a really terrible job in that, I have to say.

445
00:27:17,440 --> 00:27:19,970
字幕
Really? You didn't like yourself? I didn't see it.

446
00:27:26,600 --> 00:27:29,490
字幕
He was always trying to be a holistic person,

447
00:27:29,660 --> 00:27:33,210
字幕
the fight, the philosophy, the better human being.

448
00:27:33,210 --> 00:27:38,480
字幕
Martial art has a very, very deep meaning as far as my life is concerned.

449
00:27:38,480 --> 00:27:40,110
字幕
And he was a very literate guy.

450
00:27:40,110 --> 00:27:41,320
字幕
He really did read

451
00:27:41,320 --> 00:27:43,370
字幕
and really did study and really did think.

452
00:27:43,790 --> 00:27:47,950
字幕
All type of knowledge ultimately means self-knowledge.

453
00:27:47,950 --> 00:27:53,070
字幕
He had a huge library of books in his den from the ceiling to the floor.

454
00:27:53,070 --> 00:27:56,520
字幕
Any book I'd pick up, there were notations about what was good,

455
00:27:56,520 --> 00:27:58,430
字幕
what was functional, what was no good.

456
00:27:58,430 --> 00:28:03,330
字幕
As an actor, as a martial artist, as a human being,

457
00:28:03,330 --> 00:28:07,100
字幕
all these I have learned from martial art.

458
00:28:07,100 --> 00:28:11,300
字幕
Most of the writings in the Tao of Jeet Kune Do are Western influenced

459
00:28:11,300 --> 00:28:14,490
字幕
and they come directly from fencing and boxing books.

460
00:28:14,490 --> 00:28:17,410
字幕
And you can take most of the passages in that book

461
00:28:17,410 --> 00:28:19,760
字幕
and trace them to their roots, verbatim.

462
00:28:19,920 --> 00:28:24,190
字幕
He might have changed "fighter" from "fencer", but pretty much it's intact.

463
00:28:24,190 --> 00:28:27,280
字幕
People will say, "Hey, that's not Bruce's philosophy."

464
00:28:27,280 --> 00:28:29,630
字幕
"That was this author or that author."

465
00:28:29,630 --> 00:28:31,740
字幕
That doesn't matter. These people are missing the point.

466
00:28:31,740 --> 00:28:34,440
字幕
Bruce Lee's writings are very fun to read, but they were notes.

467
00:28:34,440 --> 00:28:37,530
字幕
You get these quotes where he may change one word

468
00:28:37,530 --> 00:28:40,220
字幕
and substitute jeet kune do for tao.

469
00:28:40,220 --> 00:28:44,720
字幕
So therefore it's not pure naturalness or unnaturalness.

470
00:28:44,950 --> 00:28:50,050
字幕
The ideal is unnatural naturalness or natural unnaturalness.

471
00:28:50,140 --> 00:28:52,390
字幕
- Yin yang. - You're right, man, that's it.

472
00:28:52,390 --> 00:28:55,580
字幕
Because of Bruce Lee, now I read up on Alan Watts.

473
00:28:55,770 --> 00:28:59,390
字幕
JD Krishnamurti, of course Lao Tsu,

474
00:28:59,390 --> 00:29:00,770
字幕
Tao Te Ching.

475
00:29:00,770 --> 00:29:03,640
字幕
Bruce Lee dissected those philosophies,

476
00:29:03,640 --> 00:29:06,490
字幕
making them straight and direct and to the point.

477
00:29:06,490 --> 00:29:08,120
字幕
That's what real philosophy's about,

478
00:29:08,120 --> 00:29:11,020
字幕
something that you can apply to day-to-day living.

479
00:29:11,020 --> 00:29:12,380
字幕
That's what Bruce Lee did.

480
00:29:12,380 --> 00:29:14,350
字幕
This is where he was a genius.

481
00:29:14,350 --> 00:29:16,090
字幕
It might sound too philosophical,

482
00:29:16,090 --> 00:29:20,440
字幕
but it's unacting acting or acting unacting if you...

483
00:29:20,590 --> 00:29:23,300
字幕
- You've lost me. - I have, huh?

484
00:29:23,300 --> 00:29:28,800
字幕
So Bruce Lee as a philosopher introduces nothing new

485
00:29:28,800 --> 00:29:32,380
字幕
but introduces a radicalism into martial art.

486
00:29:32,380 --> 00:29:35,220
字幕
He's speaking the ideology of the counterculture.

487
00:29:35,220 --> 00:29:37,220
字幕
He speaks the zeitgeist.

488
00:29:37,220 --> 00:29:41,600
字幕
So you get an interest in Buddhism, in yoga, in all things Eastern.

489
00:29:41,600 --> 00:29:44,620
字幕
Bruce Lee shows you meditation in movement.

490
00:29:47,650 --> 00:29:49,180
字幕
You set up a school in Hollywood

491
00:29:49,180 --> 00:29:52,820
字幕
for people like James Garner, Steve McQueen and the others.

492
00:29:52,820 --> 00:29:57,120
字幕
Why would they want to learn Chinese martial art? Because of a movie role?

493
00:29:57,260 --> 00:29:58,180
字幕
Not really.

494
00:29:58,180 --> 00:30:02,340
字幕
Most of them, you see, they are coming in to ask me to teach them

495
00:30:02,340 --> 00:30:04,750
字幕
not so much how to defend themselves,

496
00:30:04,750 --> 00:30:07,170
字幕
they want to learn to express themselves

497
00:30:07,170 --> 00:30:09,530
字幕
through some movement, be it anger,

498
00:30:09,970 --> 00:30:12,410
字幕
be it determination or whatsoever.

499
00:30:12,410 --> 00:30:16,380
字幕
He is paying me to show him in combative form

500
00:30:16,380 --> 00:30:19,070
字幕
the art of expressing the human body.

501
00:30:20,640 --> 00:30:23,440
字幕
Our back yard was always a back yard school,

502
00:30:23,440 --> 00:30:25,070
字幕
so for Jim Coburn to come over

503
00:30:25,070 --> 00:30:26,590
字幕
or Steve McQueen to come over

504
00:30:26,590 --> 00:30:28,890
字幕
was like not that big a deal.

505
00:30:28,890 --> 00:30:32,130
字幕
Of all your students, famous, James Garner, Steve McQueen,

506
00:30:32,130 --> 00:30:34,760
字幕
James Coburn, Roman Polanski, which was the best?

507
00:30:34,760 --> 00:30:40,410
字幕
Depending, OK? Now, as a fighter, Steve McQueen, that son of a gun,

508
00:30:40,410 --> 00:30:42,650
字幕
got the toughness in him.

509
00:30:42,650 --> 00:30:45,330
字幕
Now, James Coburn is a peace-loving man.

510
00:30:45,330 --> 00:30:47,090
字幕
- I've met him. - You've met him.

511
00:30:47,090 --> 00:30:49,170
字幕
He's really, really nice.

512
00:30:49,170 --> 00:30:52,700
字幕
Super mellow and all that, you know what I mean?

513
00:30:52,700 --> 00:30:55,690
字幕
Now, he appreciates the philosophical part of it,

514
00:30:55,690 --> 00:30:58,500
字幕
therefore his understanding of it is deeper than Steve's.

515
00:30:58,500 --> 00:31:01,010
字幕
He often told me, "I would like to see Steve McQueen

516
00:31:01,010 --> 00:31:02,720
字幕
be a little bit more like Coburn

517
00:31:02,720 --> 00:31:05,230
字幕
and Coburn to be a little bit more like Steve McQueen."

518
00:31:05,230 --> 00:31:08,360
字幕
Actually, you see, it's a combination of both.

519
00:31:08,360 --> 00:31:12,680
字幕
I mean, here is the natural instinct and here is control.

520
00:31:12,870 --> 00:31:15,690
字幕
You are to combine the two in harmony.

521
00:31:16,170 --> 00:31:19,020
字幕
Not if you have one to the extreme,

522
00:31:19,020 --> 00:31:21,140
字幕
you will be very unscientific.

523
00:31:21,140 --> 00:31:23,450
字幕
If you have another to the extreme,

524
00:31:23,450 --> 00:31:26,460
字幕
you become all of a sudden a mechanical man.

525
00:31:30,370 --> 00:31:34,850
字幕
All the big, big names in tournament fighting came to Bruce

526
00:31:34,850 --> 00:31:36,860
字幕
because they wanted to refine their skills.

527
00:31:36,860 --> 00:31:39,230
字幕
Joe Lewis, Bob Wall, Chuck Norris.

528
00:31:39,230 --> 00:31:41,520
字幕
Chuck Norris was probably the greatest kicker I've ever seen.

529
00:31:41,520 --> 00:31:43,980
字幕
Chuck Norris is unbelievable.

530
00:31:43,980 --> 00:31:45,730
字幕
Bruce didn't want to teach beginners.

531
00:31:45,730 --> 00:31:48,370
字幕
He did have some in his own schools.

532
00:31:48,450 --> 00:31:51,810
字幕
But he took the top martial artists and he felt he could make them better.

533
00:31:51,810 --> 00:31:54,800
字幕
"One more time. You don't get it, we move to something else."

534
00:31:54,800 --> 00:31:56,890
字幕
"You gonna get it?" That's how he would teach.

535
00:31:56,890 --> 00:31:59,500
字幕
He knew a lot. He taught me gung fu.

536
00:31:59,500 --> 00:32:02,130
字幕
Joe Lewis was highly influenced by Bruce Lee.

537
00:32:02,130 --> 00:32:04,210
字幕
Joe Lewis was a world champion when he met Bruce,

538
00:32:04,210 --> 00:32:08,010
字幕
but it was a lot more of Bruce being the instructor to Joe.

539
00:32:08,010 --> 00:32:11,170
字幕
I don't think he had boxing hands until he met Bruce Lee,

540
00:32:11,170 --> 00:32:13,140
字幕
but his side kick was phenomenal.

541
00:32:13,140 --> 00:32:15,300
字幕
Joe would throw 1,000 side kicks a day.

542
00:32:15,300 --> 00:32:19,620
字幕
Listen, Joe Lewis, in today's world, he would have learned all that shit

543
00:32:19,620 --> 00:32:22,540
字幕
and been just as bad as he was back in the day.

544
00:32:22,540 --> 00:32:26,170
字幕
Bruce didn't think point karate, point martial arts competition,

545
00:32:26,170 --> 00:32:28,820
字幕
was valuable at all, and I totally disagreed with him.

546
00:32:28,820 --> 00:32:31,530
字幕
Bruce watched it but didn't believe in it.

547
00:32:31,530 --> 00:32:34,060
字幕
He always advocated full-contact sparring.

548
00:32:34,060 --> 00:32:37,280
字幕
Bruce Lee looked at all of that and said, "This is not martial arts."

549
00:32:37,280 --> 00:32:39,750
字幕
"This is nonsense. Let's get rid of these rules."

550
00:32:39,750 --> 00:32:42,640
字幕
I respect that he didn't feel like he wanted to compete

551
00:32:42,640 --> 00:32:44,120
字幕
because it wasn't real combat.

552
00:32:44,120 --> 00:32:47,640
字幕
He says you're not fighting for yourself or expressing yourself.

553
00:32:47,640 --> 00:32:50,370
字幕
You're fighting for the judges, the referee, the rules.

554
00:32:50,370 --> 00:32:54,740
字幕
What's the reality of combat? There's someone who wants to beat you down.

555
00:32:54,740 --> 00:32:57,860
字幕
He said to learn to swim, you cannot swim on land.

556
00:32:57,860 --> 00:32:59,480
字幕
You gotta get in the water.

557
00:32:59,570 --> 00:33:01,810
字幕
To learn to fight, you gotta fight.

558
00:33:02,120 --> 00:33:05,720
字幕
Can you break five or six pieces of wood with your hand or your foot?

559
00:33:05,720 --> 00:33:07,740
字幕
Boards don't hit back.

560
00:33:07,740 --> 00:33:09,720
字幕
I'll probably break my hand and foot.

561
00:33:10,450 --> 00:33:13,660
字幕
He had high regard for those martial artists of the day

562
00:33:13,660 --> 00:33:15,350
字幕
that were winning tournaments.

563
00:33:15,350 --> 00:33:20,780
字幕
He just had a different philosophy about martial arts and actual fighting.

564
00:33:23,970 --> 00:33:26,690
字幕
I do not believe in styles any more.

565
00:33:26,690 --> 00:33:30,550
字幕
I mean, I do not believe that there is such thing

566
00:33:30,550 --> 00:33:33,150
字幕
as like a Chinese way of fighting

567
00:33:33,150 --> 00:33:37,370
字幕
or the Japanese way of fighting or whatever way of fighting.

568
00:33:37,370 --> 00:33:39,370
字幕
Because if you don't have styles,

569
00:33:39,370 --> 00:33:43,200
字幕
if you just say, "Well, here I am, you know, as a human being,

570
00:33:43,200 --> 00:33:47,540
字幕
how can I express myself totally and completely?"

571
00:33:47,540 --> 00:33:53,380
字幕
Now, that way, you won't create a style, because style is a crystallisation.

572
00:33:53,380 --> 00:33:57,290
字幕
I mean, that way it's a process of continuing growth.

573
00:33:57,480 --> 00:34:00,210
字幕
He called his institute Jun Fan Gung Fu.

574
00:34:00,210 --> 00:34:04,670
字幕
We were riding in a car and he mentioned what he enjoyed in fencing

575
00:34:04,670 --> 00:34:06,110
字幕
was the stop hit.

576
00:34:07,240 --> 00:34:10,650
字幕
Bruce didn't have any passive blocks. His blocks were a strike.

577
00:34:10,810 --> 00:34:14,730
字幕
Bruce took the stances from the stances that you see in Western fencing.

578
00:34:16,520 --> 00:34:20,200
字幕
Instead of just block and then hit, it's done simultaneously.

579
00:34:20,660 --> 00:34:24,120
字幕
He says we wanna intercept his physical motion and his thought.

580
00:34:24,120 --> 00:34:27,190
字幕
It's almost like fencing. You see this capture? That's the capture.

581
00:34:29,550 --> 00:34:34,430
字幕
And that's why he said, "I'm gonna call my new method the intercepting way

582
00:34:34,430 --> 00:34:36,540
字幕
or the intercepting fist."

583
00:34:36,540 --> 00:34:38,650
字幕
Come on, touch me. Any way you can.

584
00:34:40,370 --> 00:34:42,380
字幕
To reach me, you must move to me.

585
00:34:42,590 --> 00:34:45,440
字幕
Your attack offers me an opportunity to intercept you.

586
00:34:45,440 --> 00:34:46,740
字幕
And they said, "What do you call that?"

587
00:34:46,740 --> 00:34:50,100
字幕
He says, "We call thatjeet kune do."

588
00:34:50,100 --> 00:34:52,070
字幕
In Cantonese, jeet kune do.

589
00:34:52,070 --> 00:34:56,230
字幕
Then it was Dan who says, "Acronym would be JKD."

