Obviously out of China you have Jet Li, you have Donnie Yen.

1037
01:00:14,580 --> 01:00:20,880
字幕
There have been no great Asian male leads in Hollywood who are sexy.

1038
01:00:21,080 --> 01:00:23,950
字幕
Er, a lead male, Asian-American?

1039
01:00:24,170 --> 01:00:25,170
字幕
Erm...

1040
01:00:26,030 --> 01:00:30,290
字幕
I don't even look at him as being Asian. He's like Bruce Lee. He's like my idol.

1041
01:00:30,290 --> 01:00:34,090
字幕
And that's something I guess I don't think of so much, but I guess, yeah.

1042
01:00:34,170 --> 01:00:35,520
字幕
A Chinese nationalist

1043
01:00:35,520 --> 01:00:38,290
字幕
watching Bruce Lee films will see Chinese nationalism.

1044
01:00:38,290 --> 01:00:41,160
字幕
A white Westerner may not even notice the ethnicity.

1045
01:00:41,160 --> 01:00:43,930
字幕
Maybe Dean Cain, right?

1046
01:00:44,260 --> 01:00:45,560
字幕
Isn't he part Asian?

1047
01:00:46,980 --> 01:00:50,270
字幕
At certain times there were prejudices against my skin,

1048
01:00:50,270 --> 01:00:54,030
字幕
but I never let it bother me, because in the back of my mind I used to think,

1049
01:00:54,030 --> 01:00:57,710
字幕
"I'll take care out in the parking lot and I'll beat your head in."

1050
01:00:57,710 --> 01:01:02,460
字幕
Bruce Lee became a complete star making films in his own country.

1051
01:01:02,460 --> 01:01:04,620
字幕
40 years later, things haven't changed.

1052
01:01:04,620 --> 01:01:06,910
字幕
So if you wanna see another star like that,

1053
01:01:06,910 --> 01:01:09,650
字幕
it has to happen in films made outside of the system.

1054
01:01:13,620 --> 01:01:17,730
字幕
My first memory of Bruce Lee is in the movie Chinese Connection.

1055
01:01:17,730 --> 01:01:20,990
字幕
The last scene in the movie there's a firing squad.

1056
01:01:22,220 --> 01:01:26,040
字幕
When he came out and ran up and jumped and they froze it.

1057
01:01:29,210 --> 01:01:32,130
字幕
I was like, "Mom, what happened?"

1058
01:01:32,130 --> 01:01:35,780
字幕
And she said, "He wanted to go that way."

1059
01:01:35,780 --> 01:01:39,610
字幕
And that just... that just stuck with me.

1060
01:01:39,770 --> 01:01:42,490
字幕
If you look at Chinese Connection,

1061
01:01:42,490 --> 01:01:45,730
字幕
it's a movie about cultural nationalism,

1062
01:01:45,730 --> 01:01:51,040
字幕
as expressed through action sequences, but that's no different than Swan Lake.

1063
01:01:51,040 --> 01:01:54,520
字幕
There's no difference between a ballet and a kung fu movie,

1064
01:01:54,520 --> 01:01:57,870
字幕
expressing the ideas and the emotion through movement.

1065
01:02:00,780 --> 01:02:04,820
字幕
When the Japanese bring the sick man of Asia framed picture,

1066
01:02:04,820 --> 01:02:09,540
字幕
this is speaking to a long period of Chinese suppression and subordination

1067
01:02:09,540 --> 01:02:13,300
字幕
that was within living memory of those 1970s Hong Kong Bruce Lee films.

1068
01:02:15,340 --> 01:02:18,000
字幕
If you play the film with the dubbed English

1069
01:02:18,310 --> 01:02:20,140
字幕
and then in the original Cantonese,

1070
01:02:20,140 --> 01:02:22,710
字幕
you see that they're essentially different films.

1071
01:02:22,710 --> 01:02:27,150
字幕
So, for example, one of the characters goes up to Mr Wu, the translator,

1072
01:02:27,150 --> 01:02:29,530
字幕
and in the English dubbed version he says:

1073
01:02:29,530 --> 01:02:31,860
字幕
Look, here, now what's the point of this?

1074
01:02:31,860 --> 01:02:33,630
字幕
The translator goes:

1075
01:02:39,170 --> 01:02:41,840
字幕
In the Cantonese version he says:

1076
01:02:48,130 --> 01:02:50,540
字幕
So in the English version he's not Chinese,

1077
01:02:50,540 --> 01:02:55,750
字幕
but in the subtitled Cantonese version, he says, "Yes, I'm Chinese,

1078
01:02:55,750 --> 01:02:58,520
字幕
but I've chosen to go with the Japanese, the powerful."

1079
01:02:58,520 --> 01:03:00,290
字幕
So there's a world of difference.

1080
01:03:00,290 --> 01:03:01,970
字幕
We're consuming different films

1081
01:03:01,970 --> 01:03:05,210
字幕
depending on the nature of the decisions they make in translating.

1082
01:03:05,210 --> 01:03:07,640
字幕
Westerners have thought that they're slapstick,

1083
01:03:07,640 --> 01:03:11,590
字幕
but the Chinese audience are watching highly politically charged films

1084
01:03:11,590 --> 01:03:15,990
字幕
with quite recent history, animosities and resentments coursing through them.

1085
01:03:16,140 --> 01:03:20,330
字幕
Now, you listen to me, and I'll only say it once.

1086
01:03:21,010 --> 01:03:22,340
字幕
We are not sick men.

1087
01:03:22,340 --> 01:03:24,480
字幕
What he gave was so real and so raw

1088
01:03:24,480 --> 01:03:26,810
字幕
because he lived it every day of his life.

1089
01:03:27,350 --> 01:03:32,120
字幕
Bruce did not get along well with the director of the first two films, Lo Wei.

1090
01:03:32,120 --> 01:03:34,750
字幕
Lo Wei thought that he could put his thumb on Bruce

1091
01:03:34,750 --> 01:03:37,480
字幕
as one of his simple actors.

1092
01:03:37,480 --> 01:03:41,980
字幕
Well, he was old school and wouldn't listen to any ideas Bruce had.

1093
01:03:41,980 --> 01:03:45,540
字幕
The bottom line is Bruce still didn't feel the freedom that he wanted.

1094
01:03:50,150 --> 01:03:52,910
字幕
He said to Raymond Chow,

1095
01:03:52,910 --> 01:03:56,270
字幕
"I want to make this film, The Way of the Dragon."

1096
01:03:56,270 --> 01:03:59,400
字幕
I want to write it, I want to produce it, I want to direct it

1097
01:03:59,400 --> 01:04:01,440
字幕
and I can do this and act in it.

1098
01:04:01,440 --> 01:04:04,570
字幕
It's really a simple plot of a country boy

1099
01:04:04,570 --> 01:04:06,720
字幕
going to a place where he cannot speak the language

1100
01:04:06,720 --> 01:04:09,210
字幕
but somehow he came out on top.

1101
01:04:09,210 --> 01:04:14,190
字幕
Because he, well, because he honestly and simply expressed himself. 

1102
01:04:14,300 --> 01:04:16,670
字幕
He goes to Italy and the mafia can't beat him,

1103
01:04:16,670 --> 01:04:19,970
字幕
so they call America and America sends over Colt.

1104
01:04:19,970 --> 01:04:22,860
字幕
We must call America for Colt.

1105
01:04:22,860 --> 01:04:26,800
字幕
- Is this Colt good? - Is Colt good?

1106
01:04:26,800 --> 01:04:28,760
字幕
And Colt is Chuck Norris.

1107
01:04:28,760 --> 01:04:32,300
字幕
Bruce Lee is fighting a real American, you know.

1108
01:04:32,300 --> 01:04:35,670
字幕
He's strawberry blond. He's got hair all over his body.

1109
01:04:35,670 --> 01:04:37,810
字幕
In fact, he uses that hair against him.

1110
01:04:37,920 --> 01:04:40,180
字幕
So when he fought Chuck Norris...

1111
01:04:40,180 --> 01:04:42,540
字幕
Bruce Lee represented the entire third world. 

1112
01:04:42,540 --> 01:04:47,160
字幕
He represented all people of colour fighting the Western oppressor.

1113
01:04:50,760 --> 01:04:56,200
字幕
the fight between bruce lee and chuck norris in the colosseum was a classic 

1114
01:04:56,200 --> 01:05:00,740
字幕
fight to the death and bruce lee kicked his ass. 

1115
01:05:01,590 --> 01:05:04,620
字幕
If you're a non-white viewer, this is a big deal.

1116
01:05:04,620 --> 01:05:09,200
字幕
The little guy is beating the best that America can provide.

1117
01:05:09,200 --> 01:05:11,400
字幕
I can tell you, at the Fox Theatre in St Louis,

1118
01:05:11,400 --> 01:05:15,600
字幕
which was 100 percent all black, we cheered for him.

1119
01:05:15,870 --> 01:05:18,330
字幕
Some of us were more politically aware than others,

1120
01:05:18,330 --> 01:05:19,940
字幕
but everyone got the joke.

1121
01:05:24,550 --> 01:05:27,790
字幕
He was very appealing to anybody who's ever been oppressed

1122
01:05:27,790 --> 01:05:29,830
字幕
because of ethnic reasons or other reason.

1123
01:05:29,830 --> 01:05:34,060
字幕
That time when Bruce was on the rise, we were looking for countercultural heroes

1124
01:05:34,060 --> 01:05:35,060
字幕
to fight the establishment.

1125
01:05:35,060 --> 01:05:38,480
字幕
It's 40 years. Wouldn't have people forgotten him by now?

1126
01:05:39,480 --> 01:05:43,470
字幕
No, I think a lot of cultures have picked him up as sort of their hero.

1127
01:05:43,470 --> 01:05:46,860
字幕
You had Muhammad Ali. You had Malcolm X. You had the Black Panthers.

1128
01:05:46,860 --> 01:05:49,350
字幕
You had a lot of radicalism going on.

1129
01:05:49,560 --> 01:05:51,940
字幕
Bruce Lee represented that same kind of radicalism.

1130
01:05:51,940 --> 01:05:55,850
字幕
Bruce Lee emerges when America is having a very bad time in Vietnam

1131
01:05:55,850 --> 01:05:58,600
字幕
and cannot beat the Viet Cong,

1132
01:05:58,600 --> 01:06:01,580
字幕
these little yellow guys in pyjamas,

1133
01:06:01,580 --> 01:06:03,440
字幕
so Bruce Lee speaks to that.

1134
01:06:03,670 --> 01:06:07,940
字幕
Anywhere you go, everybody is about Bruce Lee and rallies behind him.

1135
01:06:07,940 --> 01:06:09,030
字幕
He's the underdog.

1136
01:06:09,030 --> 01:06:12,700
字幕
You don't have to start shouting political declarations

1137
01:06:12,700 --> 01:06:14,990
字幕
to be culturally and politically significant.

1138
01:06:14,990 --> 01:06:18,540
字幕
That Colosseum fight was very accurate. Taking nothing away from Chuck Norris,

1139
01:06:18,540 --> 01:06:20,990
字幕
but I think Bruce Lee would be victorious.

1140
01:06:20,990 --> 01:06:23,960
字幕
That fight scene gave Chuck Norris pretty much a career.

1141
01:06:24,120 --> 01:06:26,860
字幕
If they said Bruce could have beat Chuck Norris,

1142
01:06:26,860 --> 01:06:29,340
字幕
I'd say, "How much do you wanna bet?"

1143
01:06:29,340 --> 01:06:32,130
字幕
I got a fistful of green backs in my pocket.

1144
01:06:33,340 --> 01:06:36,320
字幕
Chuck got chucked out right there in that movie.

1145
01:06:36,320 --> 01:06:40,660
字幕
That's one of my favourites. Boom. Guillotine choke in the '70s. Hello.

1146
01:06:40,660 --> 01:06:42,730
字幕
That's being ahead of your time.

1147
01:06:43,920 --> 01:06:47,180
字幕
When Bruce started doing the film Way of the Dragon

1148
01:06:47,180 --> 01:06:49,460
字幕
and he was this huge star on the rise,

1149
01:06:49,460 --> 01:06:50,860
字幕
things were changing.

1150
01:06:52,000 --> 01:06:55,380
字幕
I think he started having a hard time trusting people around him.

1151
01:06:55,380 --> 01:06:57,160
字幕
You bastard!

1152
01:06:59,450 --> 01:07:02,880
字幕
Fame is a killer, literally.

1153
01:07:02,880 --> 01:07:04,650
字幕
Put money on top of that.

1154
01:07:04,650 --> 01:07:08,520
字幕
Suddenly you distrust people's motives, for very good reason.

1155
01:07:14,460 --> 01:07:18,210
字幕
He had told me that he doesn't know who his friends were.

1156
01:07:18,210 --> 01:07:20,070
字幕
He says he doesn't know who to trust.

1157
01:07:20,170 --> 01:07:25,150
字幕
It was eye-opening to know what the price of fame was.

1158
01:07:25,150 --> 01:07:27,040
字幕
well, let me put it this way, 

1159
01:07:27,230 --> 01:07:30,590
字幕
to be honest and all that, I am not as bad as some of them

1160
01:07:30,590 --> 01:07:33,860
字幕
 but I definitely am not saying that I am a saint.

1161
01:07:35,170 --> 01:07:39,100
字幕
You can't go to school for it. You deal with it on a day-to-day basis.

1162
01:07:39,100 --> 01:07:41,750
字幕
I cannot, you know, speak as freely as I,

1163
01:07:41,750 --> 01:07:43,410
字幕
 you know, could before, because....

1164
01:07:43,800 --> 01:07:48,170
字幕
misinterpretation comes in and, I mean, you know, all kinds of things.

1165
01:07:48,420 --> 01:07:50,570
字幕
Fame took over my mind.

1166
01:07:50,570 --> 01:07:53,320
字幕
It almost destroyed my career, my family.

1167
01:07:53,320 --> 01:07:54,880
字幕
I was caught up in my own hype.

1168
01:07:54,880 --> 01:07:58,160
字幕
I thought the only way to save myself from myself

1169
01:07:58,160 --> 01:08:02,990
字幕
was to do something where I could get hit and hit back.

1170
01:08:03,100 --> 01:08:04,680
字幕
And I thought I'd made a healthy choice

1171
01:08:04,680 --> 01:08:08,820
字幕
because it was better than a whisky bottle or, you know, whatever the fuck.

1172
01:08:08,820 --> 01:08:09,840
字幕
It got to the point

1173
01:08:09,840 --> 01:08:13,930
字幕
where he could hardly go out of the house without people following him.

1174
01:08:13,930 --> 01:08:17,220
字幕
He craved on sort of a soul level

1175
01:08:17,220 --> 01:08:20,140
字幕
to be a little bit more peaceful.

1176
01:08:20,140 --> 01:08:22,850
字幕
It’s strange in the sense that it’s like I’m in jail, 

1177
01:08:22,850 --> 01:08:25,520
字幕
you know what I mean? I am like a monkey in the zoo,

1178
01:08:25,520 --> 01:08:28,350
字幕
 you know? People looking at me and things like that.

1179
01:08:28,850 --> 01:08:30,750
字幕
Well, you can't have a normal life

1180
01:08:30,750 --> 01:08:32,570
字幕
or make normal mistakes

1181
01:08:33,010 --> 01:08:36,840
字幕
because everybody's constantly, you know, looking in.

1182
01:08:38,590 --> 01:08:41,290
字幕
And it was just like a smorgasbord.

1183
01:08:41,290 --> 01:08:44,110
字幕
He could have had ten at a time if he even remotely wanted to.

1184
01:08:44,670 --> 01:08:48,580
字幕
The word superstar really turned me off and I'll tell you why.

1185
01:08:48,580 --> 01:08:52,360
字幕
Because the word star, man, it's an illusion.

1186
01:08:52,360 --> 01:08:55,340
字幕
It's something what the public calls you.

1187
01:08:59,960 --> 01:09:02,290
字幕
I really loved... I might get

1188
01:09:02,290 --> 01:09:05,620
字幕
a lot of crap for this, but Game of Death,

1189
01:09:06,040 --> 01:09:07,950
字幕
and to have like no way is the way.

1190
01:09:07,950 --> 01:09:12,050
字幕
He's fighting each opponent that brings a different problem to the table

1191
01:09:12,050 --> 01:09:13,090
字幕
and he's gotta adapt.

1192
01:09:13,090 --> 01:09:18,390
字幕
Kareem Abdul-Jabbar came to Hong Kong to visit and Bruce had this great idea.

1193
01:09:18,390 --> 01:09:22,920
字幕
"Let's do a scene together. It'll be great, a great fighting sequence."

1194
01:09:22,920 --> 01:09:25,910
字幕
I'd speak to Kareem about his sessions with Bruce and he said,

1195
01:09:25,910 --> 01:09:29,040
字幕
"I sparred with him and like he was just so quick."

1196
01:09:29,040 --> 01:09:31,440
字幕
"I'd turn this way and then he's not there."

1197
01:09:31,440 --> 01:09:33,440
字幕
"He's kicking you in the back of the head."

1198
01:09:33,440 --> 01:09:35,400
字幕
"Then I turn this way and he's over here."

1199
01:09:35,590 --> 01:09:40,240
字幕
He said he couldn't catch him. There was just no way he could lock in on him.

1200
01:09:40,240 --> 01:09:42,550
字幕
He was just like a rabbit.

1201
01:09:42,850 --> 01:09:48,460
字幕
I really love the idea of the levels and getting to the next level,

1202
01:09:48,460 --> 01:09:50,850
字幕
and fighting different styles.

1203
01:09:50,850 --> 01:09:55,190
字幕
As a dancer who battled other dancers, that was like the whole mentality.

1204
01:09:55,190 --> 01:09:59,150
字幕
And on the third level, it's supposed to be a person who is trained in weaponry,

1205
01:09:59,280 --> 01:10:01,530
字幕
and so he chose me to do the part.

1206
01:10:01,940 --> 01:10:05,260
字幕
Dan lnosanto, being one of the freshest Filipinos on the planet,

1207
01:10:05,260 --> 01:10:07,990
字幕
was actually the person that brought the nunchucks to Bruce Lee.

1208
01:10:08,320 --> 01:10:12,260
字幕
1964, I introduced the nunchucks to Bruce Lee.

1209
01:10:12,600 --> 01:10:16,910
字幕
And at the time he thought this was a worthless piece of junk.

1210
01:10:28,830 --> 01:10:32,130
字幕
When he moved into the LA area, I taught him how to use it.

1211
01:10:32,390 --> 01:10:34,670
字幕
He said, "I'm gonna use this on The Green Hornet."

1212
01:10:36,160 --> 01:10:40,330
字幕
Nunchucks was always some mother's broom getting sacrificed,

1213
01:10:40,330 --> 01:10:43,740
字幕
which would then turn into someone's groin being sacrificed.

1214
01:10:43,740 --> 01:10:47,140
字幕
In three months he was swinging it like he had been doing it for a lifetime.

1215
01:10:47,390 --> 01:10:49,700
字幕
I was living in Miami when they came out.

1216
01:10:49,700 --> 01:10:53,520
字幕
Every gangster in town had nunchucks, and couldn't use 'em worth a shit.

1217
01:10:53,520 --> 01:10:56,880
字幕
I would spend hours whipping 'em around and trying to learn the moves,

1218
01:10:56,880 --> 01:11:00,210
字幕
trying to copy how he'd have it under his shoulder right here

1219
01:11:00,210 --> 01:11:01,890
字幕
and have the hand out.

1220
01:11:01,890 --> 01:11:05,280
字幕
In a short time I think almost every child is using this.

1221
01:11:05,280 --> 01:11:08,990
字幕
It became like a household product. It's outlawed now in California.

1222
01:11:10,880 --> 01:11:14,730
字幕
After I watched this movie, I used to use that.

1223
01:11:15,330 --> 01:11:18,050
字幕
But I always hit my elbow.

1224
01:11:18,810 --> 01:11:20,410
字幕
Whaaa!

1225
01:11:20,410 --> 01:11:24,160
字幕
Right out of the gate I swung real hard and I even made the Bruce Lee noise.

1226
01:11:24,160 --> 01:11:27,130
字幕
I went, "Whoo!" and I hit my head

1227
01:11:27,130 --> 01:11:30,320
字幕
and there was this big nut that came out maybe an inch.

1228
01:11:30,320 --> 01:11:32,480
字幕
And after that I stopped making the noise

1229
01:11:32,480 --> 01:11:34,080
字幕
and I stopped playing with the nunchucks.

1230
01:11:35,080 --> 01:11:38,560
字幕
I tried to make my parents buy me some real ones. Thank God they didn't.

1231
01:11:38,560 --> 01:11:41,400
字幕
I'm nunchucking, I'm busting myself all in the head.

1232
01:11:41,400 --> 01:11:43,900
字幕
I had the rubber ones, so I'm good.

1233
01:11:45,410 --> 01:11:49,170
字幕
I got into it because I stopped carrying a gun. I carried a gun for years.

1234
01:11:49,170 --> 01:11:50,860
字幕
I'm not ashamed to admit it.

1235
01:11:50,860 --> 01:11:54,430
字幕
I think I went into therapy and I thought, "Let me carry something else."

1236
01:11:55,640 --> 01:11:57,560
字幕
This one particularly is sentimental for me.

1237
01:11:57,560 --> 01:12:00,920
字幕
These are the same nunchucks that we used in The Game of Death.

1238
01:12:02,630 --> 01:12:04,600
字幕
He gave me these to keep in the house.

1239
01:12:04,600 --> 01:12:07,300
字幕
It brings out really fond memories for me.

1240
01:12:15,460 --> 01:12:18,220
字幕
Fred Weintraub, who was an executive at Warner Bros,

1241
01:12:18,220 --> 01:12:21,680
字幕
comes to visit him in Hong Kong on the set of Game of Death,

1242
01:12:21,680 --> 01:12:24,210
字幕
says, "Hey, man, we've seen what you can do."

1243
01:12:24,210 --> 01:12:28,570
字幕
"We wanna do a film with you and we wanna do it with Warner Bros." Boom.

1244
01:12:28,570 --> 01:12:32,260
字幕
It was a time when Bruce had so much opportunity

1245
01:12:32,260 --> 01:12:36,110
字幕
and he was so thrilled to co-produce Enter the Dragon.

1246
01:12:36,110 --> 01:12:40,610
字幕
He said, "This is my opening back into Hollywood."

1247
01:12:48,360 --> 01:12:50,310
字幕
They were all there in Hong Kong,

1248
01:12:50,310 --> 01:12:53,850
字幕
the producers, Fred Weintraub, Paul Heller.

1249
01:12:53,850 --> 01:12:58,850
字幕
They're ready to film, have all this crew, Western crew, Chinese crew,

1250
01:12:58,850 --> 01:13:02,290
字幕
which was a very difficult situation in itself,

1251
01:13:02,380 --> 01:13:06,170
字幕
and sets are built, and Bruce won't come to work.

1252
01:13:08,250 --> 01:13:13,030
字幕
He wants to put a little more Chinese philosophy that fits in with the story.

1253
01:13:13,030 --> 01:13:15,200
字幕
Bruce knew what he wanted Dragon to be,

1254
01:13:15,200 --> 01:13:17,790
字幕
but had problems with folks who didn't share his vision.

1255
01:13:17,790 --> 01:13:20,400
字幕
And he was adamant he was not going to the set.

1256
01:13:20,400 --> 01:13:25,530
字幕
It was kind of hard around our house because was Bruce was so frustrated.

1257
01:13:25,530 --> 01:13:26,610
字幕
He could lose his temper.

1258
01:13:26,610 --> 01:13:29,630
字幕
If he didn't like anything you did, he would tell you.

1259
01:13:29,630 --> 01:13:31,090
字幕
Linda was that fabulous wife.

1260
01:13:31,090 --> 01:13:34,520
字幕
She knew how to talk to him and counsel him.

1261
01:13:34,520 --> 01:13:39,040
字幕
I was talking behind the scenes to Fred and Paul and the other people,

1262
01:13:39,040 --> 01:13:44,640
字幕
saying, "You need to listen to what he has to say because he is right."

1263
01:13:44,640 --> 01:13:47,530
字幕
He was fighting for his career.

1264
01:13:47,680 --> 01:13:52,530
字幕
It was a coming together, and, yes, Bruce did get things in that film.

1265
01:13:52,530 --> 01:13:54,120
字幕
Let me think.

1266
01:13:54,870 --> 01:13:57,750
字幕
Don't think. Feel.

1267
01:13:57,980 --> 01:14:01,100
字幕
And they're all better off, the world is better off,

1268
01:14:01,300 --> 01:14:03,920
字幕
for the stand that he took that time.

1269
01:14:06,590 --> 01:14:07,780
字幕
Action.

1270
01:14:09,920 --> 01:14:13,140
字幕
Enter the Dragon was Hollywood's first dipping its toe

1271
01:14:13,140 --> 01:14:15,550
字幕
into the water of the martial art genre.

1272
01:14:15,980 --> 01:14:19,560
字幕
Bruce Lee is explosive in a way that no one had seen before.

1273
01:14:23,700 --> 01:14:29,490
字幕
The opening scene, Bruce Lee basically put the mixed martial arts in his film.

1274
01:14:29,760 --> 01:14:31,650
字幕
Fighting in the kenpo gloves.

1275
01:14:31,650 --> 01:14:34,770
字幕
The mixed martial arts gloves with the open fingers.

1276
01:14:34,770 --> 01:14:36,060
字幕
And he used arm bars.

1277
01:14:36,060 --> 01:14:39,420
字幕
There's not a lot of charisma in a straight arm bar.

1278
01:14:39,420 --> 01:14:41,060
字幕
He was the man.

1279
01:14:43,380 --> 01:14:46,820
字幕
When he stomps out Bob Wall and kills him...

1280
01:14:48,020 --> 01:14:52,160
字幕
you see a lot of complex emotions all going on at once.

1281
01:14:52,260 --> 01:14:55,410
字幕
I haven't seen any actor in an action film

1282
01:14:55,410 --> 01:14:59,870
字幕
match all those levels and nuances in the middle of a fight scene.

1283
01:15:00,700 --> 01:15:04,490
字幕
The mirror scene was just, you know, when he's walking around

1284
01:15:04,490 --> 01:15:09,830
字幕
and he's cut up and all of a sudden he hears his master in his head

1285
01:15:09,830 --> 01:15:12,220
字幕
saying if you destroy the image...

1286
01:15:12,220 --> 01:15:16,030
字幕
Destroy the image and you will break the enemy.

1287
01:15:16,030 --> 01:15:17,050
字幕
You defeat the enemy,

1288
01:15:17,050 --> 01:15:19,320
字幕
he was just... It had a tension

1289
01:15:19,550 --> 01:15:23,930
字幕
that to me resonates because it's cutting through all illusions.

1290
01:15:24,500 --> 01:15:26,750
字幕
This is the moment that he was waiting for.

1291
01:15:26,750 --> 01:15:29,380
字幕
This was Bruce Lee's film in Hollywood.

1292
01:15:33,430 --> 01:15:36,450
字幕
Bruce was in a studio doing dubbing for Enter the Dragon

1293
01:15:36,450 --> 01:15:39,970
字幕
and he went to the restroom and he collapsed.

1294
01:15:39,970 --> 01:15:42,400
字幕
I was called and came to the hospital.

1295
01:15:42,400 --> 01:15:47,710
字幕
And he was unconscious and I was talking to him,

1296
01:15:47,710 --> 01:15:52,380
字幕
and he told me later that he was like in the bottom of a well

1297
01:15:52,380 --> 01:15:56,210
字幕
and he could hear me calling him, "Come back, come back."

1298
01:15:56,210 --> 01:15:58,600
字幕
And he did recover from that.

1299
01:15:58,600 --> 01:16:03,430
字幕
It was a cerebral oedema, a pressing of fluid on the brain,

1300
01:16:03,430 --> 01:16:05,370
字幕
but they never found the cause of it.

1301
01:16:05,370 --> 01:16:09,160
字幕
Ted Wong used to always tell me, "Bruce Lee was never afraid of anything,

1302
01:16:09,580 --> 01:16:12,030
字幕
except one thing, and that's getting older."

1303
01:16:12,360 --> 01:16:15,230
字幕
He came to the United States and had a complete physical

1304
01:16:15,230 --> 01:16:17,370
字幕
and they pronounced him in perfect health

1305
01:16:17,370 --> 01:16:19,360
字幕
with the body of an 18-year-old.

1306
01:16:19,360 --> 01:16:22,660
字幕
The doctors were very reassuring.

1307
01:16:22,660 --> 01:16:26,780
字幕
He had just had a collapse. He didn't have frequent headaches.

1308
01:16:26,780 --> 01:16:28,610
字幕
Of course, they didn't have MRls then

1309
01:16:28,610 --> 01:16:31,210
字幕
to see what his brain tissue was looking like.

1310
01:16:31,210 --> 01:16:32,970
字幕
I had seen him in June.

1311
01:16:32,970 --> 01:16:36,740
字幕
He told me that he'd had an OK from UCLA that his body was fit.

1312
01:16:36,740 --> 01:16:40,500
字幕
He was not worried about himself and he was taking good care of himself.

1313
01:16:40,580 --> 01:16:42,730
字幕
Bruce Lee faces a real dilemma.

1314
01:16:42,730 --> 01:16:45,660
字幕
He's on the verge of stardom in the United States,

1315
01:16:45,660 --> 01:16:49,820
字幕
but he's just achieved superstardom as a film actor here in Hong Kong.

1316
01:16:49,820 --> 01:16:52,280
字幕
So what does he chose, the East or the West?

1317
01:16:52,280 --> 01:16:55,570
字幕
It's the kind of problem most budding movie actors would welcome.

1318
01:17:01,350 --> 01:17:05,620
字幕
I was called and told by Raymond Chow, "You should get to the hospital."

1319
01:17:05,620 --> 01:17:07,750
字幕
"They're taking Bruce to the hospital."

1320
01:17:08,070 --> 01:17:12,020
字幕
And I was there way before Bruce got there.

1321
01:17:12,270 --> 01:17:16,780
字幕
So eventually the ambulance arrived. It took a long time.

1322
01:17:17,230 --> 01:17:19,020
字幕
Everything took too long a time.

1323
01:17:19,020 --> 01:17:22,550
字幕
He got to the hospital and I saw him laying there

1324
01:17:22,860 --> 01:17:28,300
字幕
and I saw them do a big injection of something right into his heart.

1325
01:17:31,610 --> 01:17:37,450
字幕
And I remember turning to a medical person standing there and saying...

1326
01:17:37,810 --> 01:17:39,530
字幕
I couldn't say, "Is he dead?"

1327
01:17:39,530 --> 01:17:42,170
字幕
I said, "Is he alive?

1328
01:17:42,750 --> 01:17:45,870
字幕
And they shook their heads and said, "No."

1329
01:17:46,420 --> 01:17:51,120
字幕
And that was just unbelievable.

1330
01:17:51,250 --> 01:17:55,440
字幕
It must be a mistake, you know, it's not real.

1331
01:17:56,410 --> 01:17:59,240
字幕
What can I say? It was.

1332
01:18:37,900 --> 01:18:44,600
字幕
You can see how when he passed away, you know, how...

1333
01:18:46,010 --> 01:18:50,830
字幕
how difficult that was and, you know, how difficult that was for my dad.

1334
01:18:51,160 --> 01:18:53,310
字幕
It's the first time I saw my dad ever cry.

1335
01:18:54,110 --> 01:18:55,320
字幕
Yeah, that's true.

1336
01:19:00,440 --> 01:19:01,860
字幕
It was really rough.

1337
01:19:04,300 --> 01:19:05,410
字幕
Well, yeah.

1338
01:19:08,170 --> 01:19:12,040
字幕
I said, "Dan, is it true? Ls Bruce Lee dead?"

1339
01:19:12,040 --> 01:19:15,070
字幕
"I got a lot of calls." And he says, "Yeah, Rich."

1340
01:19:15,070 --> 01:19:17,330
字幕
Linda called him from Hong Kong,

1341
01:19:17,330 --> 01:19:21,320
字幕
and he was in a trance on his own and talking about Bruce Lee.

1342
01:19:21,320 --> 01:19:24,820
字幕
He was so in grief, so in mourning about Bruce's death.

1343
01:19:24,820 --> 01:19:28,840
字幕
He was just really uniquely different from everybody else.

1344
01:19:29,620 --> 01:19:33,000
字幕
My memories, they're more like glimpses.

1345
01:19:33,110 --> 01:19:37,510
字幕
But I remember primarily the funeral in Hong Kong,

1346
01:19:37,510 --> 01:19:41,220
字幕
because it was so massive, and sort of being dragged through that,

1347
01:19:41,220 --> 01:19:43,670
字幕
because it was chaotic.

1348
01:19:43,950 --> 01:19:49,090
字幕
And I remember my dad's mom taking us to get candy

1349
01:19:49,250 --> 01:19:53,190
字幕
and feeling really happy about that.

1350
01:19:55,370 --> 01:19:58,000
字幕
I was in class, actually, when Bruce Lee died.

1351
01:19:58,820 --> 01:20:01,750
字幕
There were guys in there crying, sobbing, just...

1352
01:20:01,750 --> 01:20:04,010
字幕
I mean, Bruce Lee, you know...

1353
01:20:06,400 --> 01:20:07,950
字幕
He was just... he was it.

1354
01:20:12,110 --> 01:20:14,330
字幕
Will you tell me what Teacher died of?

1355
01:20:15,080 --> 01:20:19,150
字幕
Forensic scientists from around the world came up with the conclusion

1356
01:20:19,150 --> 01:20:21,720
字幕
that he had had a hypersensitive reaction

1357
01:20:21,720 --> 01:20:25,060
字幕
to this medication that he had been given for a headache

1358
01:20:25,060 --> 01:20:28,140
字幕
and that that had caused the fluid on his brain

1359
01:20:28,940 --> 01:20:32,760
字幕
and that he had succumbed to that.

1360
01:20:34,780 --> 01:20:38,130
字幕
It's still something that people cannot believe.

1361
01:20:38,250 --> 01:20:41,830
字幕
He was well. There was nothing wrong. How could a healthy man die?

1362
01:20:41,830 --> 01:20:46,360
字幕
And then there's all this stuff about, you know, how he died,

1363
01:20:46,360 --> 01:20:48,220
字幕
the sinister way in which he died.

1364
01:20:48,220 --> 01:20:51,820
字幕
He had an aneurysm

1365
01:20:52,160 --> 01:20:55,170
字幕
or the death hands got him or, you know...

1366
01:20:55,170 --> 01:20:56,120
字幕
He was murdered.

1367
01:20:56,120 --> 01:20:58,920
字幕
They gave him the dim mak, they gave him a death touch.

1368
01:20:59,680 --> 01:21:03,100
字幕
There's absolutely positively something a little shady

1369
01:21:03,100 --> 01:21:04,560
字幕
about the way that it all went down.

1370
01:21:04,560 --> 01:21:09,460
字幕
How he could pass away at that age, you know, but it does happen,

1371
01:21:09,460 --> 01:21:12,860
字幕
so I've learned to cope with it and deal with it.

1372
01:21:13,310 --> 01:21:15,130
字幕
But it always puzzled me.

1373
01:21:15,130 --> 01:21:17,150
字幕
The fact that my family is cursed

1374
01:21:17,150 --> 01:21:21,960
字幕
and the very sad and tragic circumstance that my brother died,

1375
01:21:21,960 --> 01:21:24,440
字幕
those are sort of the themes that pop up.

1376
01:21:24,440 --> 01:21:28,670
字幕
They wrote so many stupid stories, the tong killing him and all that bullshit,

1377
01:21:28,670 --> 01:21:31,560
字幕
and he died of drugs, that sold magazines.

1378
01:21:32,020 --> 01:21:35,690
字幕
He died in Betty Ting Pei's apartment, so there's no denying that.

1379
01:21:35,690 --> 01:21:40,290
字幕
The decision was made by the producers to say that he had died at home.

1380
01:21:40,570 --> 01:21:44,110
字幕
When that news got out that he had not died at home,

1381
01:21:44,110 --> 01:21:45,360
字幕
the tabloid press went crazy.

1382
01:21:45,360 --> 01:21:49,470
字幕
But my mom knew he had been at a meeting and doing his films.

1383
01:21:49,470 --> 01:21:53,530
字幕
She was dealing with his death and taking care of her kids,

1384
01:21:53,530 --> 01:21:56,810
字幕
and all of that gossip was just the tabloid press

1385
01:21:56,810 --> 01:22:01,910
字幕
trying to make it bigger and crazier than it needed to be.

1386
01:22:04,800 --> 01:22:08,490
字幕
It is my wish that the newspapers and the people of Hong Kong

1387
01:22:08,490 --> 01:22:11,100
字幕
will stop speculating on the circumstances

1388
01:22:11,100 --> 01:22:13,090
字幕
surrounding my husband's death.

1389
01:22:13,090 --> 01:22:15,980
字幕
Please remember him for his genius, his art

1390
01:22:15,980 --> 01:22:18,920
字幕
and the magic he brought to every one of us.

1391
01:22:28,530 --> 01:22:32,680
字幕
Of course I was going to go and see his film and applaud him

1392
01:22:32,680 --> 01:22:35,100
字幕
and be with people who admired him.

1393
01:22:35,210 --> 01:22:41,120
字幕
That was always my thought in my head, is, "I need to do this for Bruce."

1394
01:22:41,120 --> 01:22:43,770
字幕
She really is this incredible woman

1395
01:22:43,770 --> 01:22:47,840
字幕
with just great dignity and grace under fire.

1396
01:22:49,540 --> 01:22:51,560
字幕
It was great to see Bruce again,

1397
01:22:51,560 --> 01:22:56,150
字幕
but only a month later my memories were very fresh anyway, you know.

1398
01:22:58,470 --> 01:23:01,780
字幕
It was more pain than joy at the time.

1399
01:23:09,170 --> 01:23:11,800
字幕
Everybody said all these years, you know,

1400
01:23:11,800 --> 01:23:16,170
字幕
he had an allergic reaction to marijuana, he had a brain aneurysm.

1401
01:23:16,170 --> 01:23:19,340
字幕
The most important thing is how he lived.

1402
01:23:21,070 --> 01:23:24,220
字幕
Every time you see him, it's still emotional.

1403
01:23:24,750 --> 01:23:26,170
字幕
We miss the friend.

1404
01:23:26,720 --> 01:23:30,650
字幕
I'm now 74, but there really has not ever been a day

1405
01:23:30,650 --> 01:23:34,700
字幕
that I haven't thought about him at least once, maybe twice

1406
01:23:34,700 --> 01:23:37,740
字幕
or three times or four times or five times through the day.

1407
01:23:37,740 --> 01:23:41,600
字幕
There's nobody who's gonna replace Bruce Lee, not while you or I are alive.

1408
01:23:41,600 --> 01:23:42,790
字幕
It just ain't gonna happen.

1409
01:23:42,790 --> 01:23:45,990
字幕
This genius passes away way before his time.

1410
01:23:45,990 --> 01:23:48,490
字幕
We have to be thankful we had him for 32 years.

1411
01:23:50,060 --> 01:23:51,500
字幕
Bruce Lee was just a symbol

1412
01:23:51,500 --> 01:23:54,520
字幕
of everything that every little boy wanted to be.

1413
01:23:54,520 --> 01:23:56,940
字幕
You have offended my family and you have...

1414
01:23:57,630 --> 01:24:00,000
字幕
Disgraced the Shaolin temple.

1415
01:24:00,740 --> 01:24:02,370
字幕
Whoo!

1416
01:24:03,220 --> 01:24:06,450
字幕
The most important thing he's ever done and accomplished

1417
01:24:06,450 --> 01:24:08,110
字幕
is bringing people together.

1418
01:24:08,110 --> 01:24:11,240
字幕
Bruce brought... he brought cultures together.

1419
01:24:11,240 --> 01:24:14,600
字幕
People remember him for being powerful beyond measure,

1420
01:24:14,600 --> 01:24:16,520
字幕
you know, for being limitless,

1421
01:24:16,520 --> 01:24:19,950
字幕
for standing for things when people crucified him.

1422
01:24:19,950 --> 01:24:22,950
字幕
It didn't matter what colour you are, what country you came from,

1423
01:24:22,950 --> 01:24:24,480
字幕
you were a Bruce Lee fan.

1424
01:24:24,480 --> 01:24:27,140
字幕
